default&#xa0;default1.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPoverty, discrimination and child rights violationsdefault: 
defaultInsufficient government investments in health, education, social welfare and social protection compound family poverty, inequality, and lack of access to basic services which lead to daily violations of children’s rights to survival, development, protection and participation. Discrimination based on ethnicity, language, religion, income, location, gender, disability and other diversity factors further contribute to child rights violations. 
defaultEach year, around 56,000 children under five die from preventable diseases in 
defaultBurma
default. 
default&#xa0;
default1.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGovernancedefault: 
defaultConstitutional and legal framework -
default The Government of 
defaultBurma (GoB
default) has ratified the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child (CRC), CEDAW, CRPD, the Optional Protocol to the CRC on the sale of children, child prostitution and child pornography, and the Charter of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations in 2008. However, the CRC does not have constitutional status in 
defaultBurma
default, thus national laws and regulations override the CRC in court. This is elaborated further under Section 4, below.
default&#xa0;
default1.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEducationdefault: At the global level, DFID has committed to the education MDGs. Studies demonstrate that education underpins progress in all aspects of development. Yet 
defaultin 
defaultBurma
default, d
defaultecades of chronic under-funding of education have resulted in poor infrastructure and facilities, lack of effective teacher training and learning materials and teaching methods that do not enable 
defaultchildren to engage actively in learning. 
defaultThe primary school completion rate is 54% overall and only 31% from the poorest households.
defaultEducation is a minor priority in DFID-B’s Operational Plan, amounting to just 5.4% of the progr
defaultamme spend forecast for 2011-15.
default&#xa0;
default1.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEducation
default is also a powerful driver of 
defaultsocial cohesiondefault. 
defaultWithin the education sector, the issue of language of instruction raises questions about the relationship between education and national identity. By developing curricula and teaching materials in the refugee camps, international donors have supported the development of a Karen education regime very different to that in government schools, and increased the isolation 
defaultof 
defaultthese populations.
default&#xa0;
default1
default.5
default defaultSocial Protection: defaultArticles 22 and 25 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (1948) define the rights of men and women to social protection. With an estimated 29% of the rural population living in poverty
default, there are many 
defaultBurmese
default people whose rights are not being met. 
defaultStudies show that by enabling poor people to invest in and develop their own production and access a nutritious diet, social transfers can lead to sustainable reductions in poverty and hunger, as well as boosting economic growth
default. 
defaultSocial protection has the potential to accelerate national growth and development by increasing productive potential and demand in local markets.
default1
default.6
default default              defaultNutritiondefault: 
defaultIn Burma, the nationwide prevalence of stunting is 35.1% and wasting is 7.9%
default,
default indicative of a serious public health problem by WHO classification. Burma
default is among the “24 high-burden countries” with the largest number of children under 5 years old who are moderately or severely stunted
default. Approximately 22.6% of all children under five are underweight. 
default&#xa0;
default1
default.7
default              
defaultThe protracted rates of under-nutrition in 
defaultBurma
default are the consequence of chronic food and nutrition insecurity, under-investment in rural development, poor health and public infrastructure, remoteness and extreme weather events. The situation is compounded in border areas by conflict and complex issues surrounding minority groups. This limits the ability of many households to access sufficient levels of nutritious food and income as 
defaultwell as basic services such as clean water, health and education. 
defaultSocial protection policies, and in particular cash transfers, allow families to meet the direct and indirect costs of a nutritious diet, healthcare and education.
default&#xa0;
default1
default.8  The main sectoral aid programmes on health (3MDG), education (MDEF/MEC) and livelihoods (LIFT) currently ignore nutrition. DFID is currently the largest contributor to the multi-
defaultdonor fund, 
defaultLivelihoods and Food Security Trust (
defaultLIFT), which is the most significant ODA initiati
defaultve on 
defaultlivelihoods 
defaultin 
defaultBurma
default. However, this fund doesn’t currently support nutrition or social protection, despite this being articulated in the LIFT strategy
default. 
